"""
Fill script: Judges mkt-christ ch14–16 — Samson narrative typology.
Fills missing verses; existing entries (ch14: 1,4,6,14,19; ch15: 14,18,19;
ch16: 17,20,28,30) are not overwritten.

Key Christological connections:
- Samson's riddle (eater/strong) = cross producing life from death
- 30 companions = 30 pieces of silver (Judas); betrayal by intimate
- Jawbone of donkey = humble instrument of divine victory
- Delilah betrayal = Judas pattern; sleep/shaving = death/humiliation
- Hair regrowth (16:22) = resurrection type
- Gaza gates carried away = harrowing of death's stronghold
- Temple pillars / outstretched arms = cruciform death that defeats more than earthly life
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

FILL = {
  "14": {
    "2": "<p>Samson reports to his father and mother: 'I saw one of the daughters of the Philistines at Timnah; now get her for me as my wife.' The direct imperative 'get her for me' bypasses the usual paternal mediation of betrothal, with Samson acting as if his desire is self-authorizing. The Christological inversion: where Samson imposes his will on his father for a bride from the wrong people, the Son of God submits his will to the Father (John 6:38) to obtain a Bride from every people — the Church gathered from the nations. Samson's bridal quest, driven by personal desire, is the shadow; Christ's acquisition of his Bride, driven by the Father's love, is the fulfillment (Eph 5:25-27).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The parents' objection — 'Is there not a woman among the daughters of your relatives, or among all our people, that you must go to take a wife from the uncircumcised Philistines?' — raises the covenant barrier: Samson is reaching across the separation between Israel and the nations. The uncircumcised (<em>ʾărēlîm</em>) were excluded from covenant standing (Gen 17:14; Exod 12:48). But v4 establishes that YHWH is working through Samson's transgression of boundaries. The type extends to Christ who crosses the ultimate covenant barrier — between God and humanity — to take a Bride from those who were 'alienated from the commonwealth of Israel and strangers to the covenants of promise' (Eph 2:12). The Bride is, from every cultural vantage point, the 'wrong' choice — uncircumcised, Gentile, once without God.</p>",
    "5": "<p>As Samson goes down to Timnah, a young lion comes roaring toward him — and the Spirit of YHWH rushes upon him, enabling him to tear the lion apart with his bare hands. The lion-kill is the first of three Spirit-empowering events in Samson's narrative (14:6, 14:19, 15:14). The Spirit as the enabler of lion-mastery connects to the promise of Ps 91:13 ('you will tread on the lion') and to the messianic figure of Gen 49:9 (Judah as a lion). The Lion of the tribe of Judah (Rev 5:5) slays the devouring lion: Christ, empowered by the Spirit in his earthly ministry (Luke 4:18), overcomes the 'roaring lion' that seeks to devour (1 Pet 5:8). The young lion (<em>kᵉpîr</em>) that threatens Samson is the same word used in Ps 34:10 for the strong who go hungry; Samson's defeat of it anticipates the triumph over every power that threatens the anointed one.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Samson goes down and speaks to the woman and she is pleasing in Samson's eyes — the language of mutual recognition and covenant pledge. The exchange between Samson and the Timnite woman initiates the betrothal that YHWH will use to provoke conflict with the Philistines. The typological frame: the engagement of the Son of God with his Bride is also an act that provokes conflict with the ruling powers of the age. Christ's covenant with his Church — sealed in his blood (Matt 26:28) — brings him into direct confrontation with the 'rulers of this age' who crucify him (1 Cor 2:8), just as Samson's covenant with the Philistine woman generates the conflict that will ultimately destroy Philistine power.</p>",
    "8": "<p>When Samson returns to take the woman, he turns aside to see the lion's carcass — and behold, a swarm of bees with honey. The honey in the dead lion is the narrative's central image and the basis for the riddle. The transformation of death into sweetness — the place of destruction becoming a source of nourishment — is the precise grammar of the atonement. Paul uses this logic in 1 Cor 15:55-56 ('O death, where is your sting?') and in Gal 3:13-14 (the curse of the cross becomes the blessing of the Spirit). Out of the dead lion — the place of Samson's act of violent killing — comes honey. Out of the dead Christ — the site of God's act of sacrificial giving — comes 'the fruit of the Spirit' (Gal 5:22): sweetness produced in the death of the strong.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Samson scoops the honey into his hands and eats as he walks, giving some to his father and mother — but he does not tell them it came from the lion's carcass (which would have made them ritually unclean, Lev 11:39). The sharing of honey from an unclean source, received without the receiver knowing its origin, is a complex typological image: the blessing that comes through Christ's death (the broken, 'unclean' body) is distributed to those who receive it without fully understanding its source. The disciples receive the bread and cup at the Last Supper without fully comprehending that they are receiving the fruit of Christ's death. The honey-bread shared from the death of the strong is the Eucharistic pattern in nascent form.</p>",
    "10": "<p>His father goes down to the woman and Samson makes a feast there — the wedding banquet. The seven-day wedding feast (<em>mišteh</em>) in an enemy territory is a type of the eschatological wedding banquet of Rev 19:7-9 hosted by the greater Son of David in a world that has not yet been fully subdued. The feast within enemy territory — celebrated while the adversary watches — prefigures the Church's Eucharistic feast celebrated during the age when the enemy has not yet been fully destroyed but has already been decisively defeated at the cross. The marriage supper is real even though the battle continues.</p>",
    "11": "<p>When the Philistines see him, they bring thirty companions to be with him. The thirty companions assigned to watch Samson — or as his groomsmen — are the narrative setup for the riddle-wager. The number thirty is typologically significant: thirty pieces of silver is the price Judas receives for betraying Jesus (Matt 26:15; Zech 11:12-13). The thirty companions of Samson who become the instruments of his betrayal through his wife parallel Judas and the thirty silver pieces — in both cases, an intimate mediates betrayal, money is the mechanism, and the betrayal results in the anointed one's captivity and humiliation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Samson offers the riddle for the seven-day feast with clothing as the prize: 'if you can tell me within the seven days of the feast what it is, I will give you thirty linen garments and thirty changes of clothes.' The seven days of the riddle-contest maps onto the seven days of creation and rest, suggesting that Samson's contest is a microcosm of the covenant order. The prize of garments (linen and festival clothing) anticipates the NT's imagery of the Bride clothed in fine linen (Rev 19:8: 'the fine linen is the righteous deeds of the saints') — the garments that the Bridegroom provides to those who solve the mystery of his death and resurrection.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Philistines accept the wager: if Samson tells them the answer, they give him the same quantity of clothing. The reciprocal wager establishes a covenant-contest over the mystery of Samson's strength. The pattern of a divine mystery embedded in apparent defeat — which the enemy cannot solve without the help of the anointed one's intimate — extends into the NT's theology of the 'mystery hidden for ages' (Col 1:26; 1 Cor 2:7). The rulers of this age could not solve the riddle of the cross and so 'crucified the Lord of glory' (1 Cor 2:8) — they could not discern that the death of the strong would produce the sweetness of resurrection.</p>",
    "15": "<p>On the fourth day the Philistine companions threaten Samson's wife: 'Entice your husband to tell us the riddle, or we will burn you and your father's house with fire.' The threat of fire against the woman and her house is the mechanism that will eventually destroy both (15:6); the enemies' coercion of Samson's intimate partner is the first instance of the betrayal pattern that will reach its fullest expression in ch16. The threatened fire prefigures the eschatological fire of judgment (2 Thess 1:7-8) — the Philistines deploy it as a weapon of coercion, but YHWH uses fire as the instrument of ultimate judgment on the same enemies (15:5).</p>",
    "16": "<p>His wife weeps before him and says, 'You only hate me; you do not love me. You have told the riddle to the sons of my people and have not told me.' The accusation 'you hate me' deployed as emotional leverage inverts the truth: Samson's refusal to tell the riddle is not hatred but the protection of the mystery's integrity. The Christological inversion: Christ's apparent silence before Pilate (Matt 27:12-14) and his refusal to perform signs on demand (Luke 23:8-9) are also read by the hostile parties as indifference or weakness, but they are the sovereign protection of the divine mystery from those who would use it destructively. The anointed one's silence is not absence but wisdom.</p>",
    "17": "<p>She weeps the remaining seven days of the feast; on the seventh day he tells her because she pressed him hard. The breaking of Samson's resistance on the seventh day anticipates the pattern of ch16 (Delilah presses him until his soul is vexed to death, v16); both collapses occur through sustained intimate pressure, and both produce catastrophic consequences. The seventh day is the day of completion and rest — Samson's revelation of the mystery on the Sabbath-day echoes the pattern of the cross on Friday followed by revelation on Sunday: the mystery of the anointed one is revealed at the moment of apparent defeat.</p>",
    "18": "<p>'What is sweeter than honey? What is stronger than a lion?' the Philistines answer. Samson responds: 'If you had not plowed with my heifer, you would not have found out my riddle.' The image of the heifer plowed by another is a covenant-violation idiom: the woman betrothed to one man used by another. Samson's riddled response — the heifer metaphor — encodes both the betrayal of intimacy and the deeper mystery: the answer to his riddle ('from the eater comes food, from the strong comes sweetness') is YHWH's way of working through apparent defeat. The Philistines have the answer but not the understanding. Knowing the riddle's words is not the same as understanding its theology, as Paul argues in 1 Cor 1:18-25: the message of the cross is 'foolishness' to those who solve it by external information rather than Spirit-given revelation.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samson's wife is given to his companion who had been his best man. The dissolution of Samson's first marriage — the bride given to the companion rather than to the groom — is the reversal of the covenant order. In the eschatological register, the Bride belongs to Christ the Bridegroom (John 3:29: 'the friend of the bridegroom, who stands and hears him, rejoices greatly at the bridegroom's voice'); the giving of the bride to the companion is the violation that the narrative builds toward correcting. Samson's first marriage is dissolved by betrayal; the covenant marriage of Christ and his Church is secured by his blood, and no betrayal can dissolve it (John 10:28-29; Rom 8:35-39).</p>"
  },
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>In the days of wheat harvest Samson visits his wife with a goat — only to find she has been given to his companion. The timing (wheat harvest) will prove significant: Samson's response will destroy the grain harvest (v5). The gift of a young goat (<em>gᵉḏî ʿizzîm</em>) echoes Jacob's deception of Isaac with a young goat (Gen 27:9) — another act where a Gentile mediator (Rebekah/the Timnite) deceives a man about the rightful recipient. The Christological reversal: Christ brings a gift not of a young goat (atonement by animal sacrifice) but of himself, and finds not a closed door but an open one — the tomb is empty and the Bridegroom is risen (Rev 3:20; Song 5:2-6).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The father offers the younger daughter instead: 'I really thought that you utterly hated her, so I gave her to your companion. Is not her younger sister more beautiful than she? Please take her instead.' The substitution of the younger for the elder in a marriage context activates the Jacob-Rachel pattern (Gen 29:26-28) and the covenant-election principle where the younger supersedes the elder (Gen 25:23; Rom 9:12). The father's offer of the substitute typologically points to Israel's historical relationship with the covenant: when the original recipient of the covenant promise fails to receive the Bridegroom, the offer extends to another (Rom 11:11-12, the Gentile church as the wild olive branch grafted in).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'This time I shall be innocent in regard to the Philistines when I do them harm.' Samson's declaration of innocence before executing judgment — <em>niqqêtî mippᵉlištîm</em> — positions his judgment as legally authorized retaliation. The theology of righteous retributive judgment that precedes mercy runs throughout the OT: YHWH declares the justice of his judgments before executing them (Exod 9:27; Neh 9:33). Christ's righteous judgment of the world is also declared innocent: YHWH has justified the Son (Isa 50:8-9; Acts 3:14-15), and it is in his righteousness that the judgment of God proceeds (John 5:30; Acts 17:31).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Samson catches three hundred foxes, turns them tail to tail, puts torches between each pair of tails. The logistical feat — three hundred foxes, each pair bound — signals supernatural organizing capacity, since catching foxes is notoriously difficult. The number three hundred recalls Gideon's three hundred (7:7-8) — YHWH works through radically reduced forces. The pairing and sending of the foxes in every direction mirrors the missionary dispersal: two by two, sent out in every direction (Luke 10:1), fire in their message (Luke 12:49: 'I came to cast fire on the earth'). The Christological mission sends pairs of disciples like living torches into the harvest fields of the nations.</p>",
    "5": "<p>He sets fire to the torches and releases the foxes into the Philistines' standing grain, and the shocks and standing grain and olive orchards are burned. The destruction of the grain, shocks, and olive orchards removes the harvest — the staple wealth of agrarian society. The fire as instrument of covenant judgment against the oppressor appears throughout the prophets (Isa 10:17; Amos 1-2). The burning of the grain fields while Israel is oppressed by Philistia is a judgment that specifically targets the harvest — the same grain that feeds the oppressor. The irony that Samson destroys the harvest at harvest-time (v1) anticipates the eschatological judgment where the harvest of the earth is reaped in judgment (Rev 14:17-20) before the final harvest of the righteous (Matt 13:30).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Philistines ask who did this; they are told it was Samson, because his father-in-law gave his wife to his companion. The Philistines burn the woman and her father with fire — the very fate they threatened the woman with in 14:15, now executed as their own act of internal punishment. The covenant logic is that the instrument of oppression destroys its own; YHWH uses the enemy's own violence to judge them. The eschatological version is Rev 17:16 where the beast turns on the harlot and burns her — the forces of anti-covenant alliance destroy each other as the inevitable culmination of a covenant built on betrayal rather than fidelity.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Samson says, 'If this is what you do, I swear I will be avenged on you, and after that I will quit.' The vow of vengeance before withdrawal is the grammar of covenant justice: the wrong must be named, the judgment declared, and then executed. The phrase 'and after that I will quit' — Samson's promise to end the conflict once justice is served — typifies the eschatological limitation of God's judgment: 'I will not always chide; nor will I be angry forever' (Ps 103:9; Isa 57:16). Christ's passion is the final execution of covenant judgment (John 12:31: 'now is the judgment of this world') after which he declares 'It is finished' (John 19:30) — the task of avenging covenant love is completed.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'He struck them hip and thigh with a great blow' — the idiom <em>šôq ʿal yāreḵ</em> (thigh upon thigh/hip and thigh) may indicate an overwhelming, total defeat; the exact idiom is disputed but the military completeness is clear. Samson then dwells in the cleft of the rock of Etam — a cave in the rock. The pattern of the anointed one retreating to a rock after a great victory anticipates Elijah's retreat to the cave at Horeb (1 Kings 19:9-10) and ultimately the resurrection: the great victory of the cross followed by the stone-sealed tomb (Matt 27:60), and then the rock opened and the stone rolled away (Matt 28:2). The rock (<em>sela</em>) as both refuge and tomb is the ambiguous dwelling of the anointed one between victory and full vindication.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Philistines encamp in Judah and spread out at Lehi. Judah's own warriors come out to ask, 'Why have you come up against us?' — and are told it is to bind Samson and do to him as he did to them. Judah's question ('Why against us?') reveals that the tribe of Judah does not yet understand that the conflict is not between Judah and Philistia but between YHWH and Philistia, and that the resolution requires Samson to be handed over. This prefigures the Jerusalem leadership's misunderstanding of the Passion: 'It is better for one man to die than for the whole nation to perish' (John 11:50) — Caiaphas also fails to understand that the handing over of the anointed one is not a political concession but the mechanism of universal liberation.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The men of Judah go to Samson and say, 'We have come down to bind you that we may give you into the hands of the Philistines.' Three thousand men of Judah come to betray their deliverer to his enemies. The reversal of covenant expectation — Judah betraying the one YHWH gave them for deliverance — anticipates the betrayal of Jesus by his own people (John 1:11: 'he came to his own, and his own people did not receive him'; John 19:15: 'we have no king but Caesar'). The three thousand echoes the three thousand who fall at the golden calf (Exod 32:28) and those who are saved at Pentecost (Acts 2:41) — the same number at the creation of the old covenant's failure and the new covenant's inauguration.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Samson asks, 'Do you not know that the Philistines are rulers over us?' — the men of Judah affirm this. The theological problem is precise: the covenant people have accepted the dominion of the covenant enemy as normal; they have accommodated themselves to oppression. This is the OT root of the NT's warning against conformity to the world (Rom 12:2) — the people of God who have become comfortable with Philistine rule see the deliverer not as their champion but as a threat to their comfortable captivity. The same dynamic drives the Passion: the Jerusalem leaders who have made peace with Roman rule (John 19:12-15) hand over the one who would upset the arrangement.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Samson agrees to let himself be bound — on one condition: that the men of Judah will not attack him themselves. 'Swear to me that you will not attack me yourselves.' The voluntary submission to binding by his own people is a type of Christ's voluntary submission to arrest in Gethsemane: 'Do you think I cannot appeal to my Father, and he will at once send me more than twelve legions of angels?' (Matt 26:53). Samson could escape; he allows the binding because it is YHWH's path to victory. The binding of the deliverer by his own people is not defeat but the necessary form of the victory that will follow.</p>",
    "13": "<p>They bind him with two new ropes and bring him up from the rock. Two ropes for the man who will snap them like thread when the Spirit comes — the binding that cannot hold the Spirit-empowered one prefigures the bonds that cannot hold the risen Christ. The stone sealed by Pilate and the chief priests (Matt 27:66) is the final 'new rope' applied to contain the anointed one; like Samson's ropes, it is temporary. The 'new ropes' detail emphasizes that no human restraint is adequate to the power of the Spirit; the resurrection breaks every chain that death and human authority can apply.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Samson finds a fresh jawbone of a donkey and kills a thousand Philistines with it. The jawbone of a donkey is the most humiliatingly humble weapon imaginable — an animal's jaw, accidentally encountered, repurposed as a war-club. Paul's theology of 1 Cor 1:27-28 ('God chose what is foolish to shame the wise; God chose what is weak to shame the strong') is typologically enacted here: the weapon of victory is the despised and discarded. The donkey's jawbone connects to the messianic imagery of Zech 9:9 (the king riding a donkey) — the same animal that carries Christ into Jerusalem also provides the weapon for this victory. Humble instruments bear the Spirit's power.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'With the jawbone of a donkey, heaps upon heaps, with the jawbone of a donkey I have struck down a thousand men.' The victory song (<em>šîr</em>) uses the wordplay <em>ḥămôr ḥămōr ḥămōrātayim</em> (donkey/heap — the Hebrew roots overlap) — Samson puns on the instrument of his victory. The song sung after a great military deliverance is the OT pattern (Exod 15; Judg 5) that reaches its fulfillment in the Revelation's vision of the song of Moses and the Lamb (Rev 15:3) — the victory song over the ultimate adversary, sung with the instrument of an apparently foolish sacrifice. The wordplay between 'donkey' and 'heap' in Samson's song is the linguistic form of the gospel's paradox: what seems foolish piles up into mountains of victory.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Samson throws the jawbone from his hand and calls the place Ramath-lehi (the hill of the jawbone). The place-naming at the site of a great victory is the OT pattern of theological memory: Ebenezer (1 Sam 7:12), Mahanaim (Gen 32:2), Peniel (Gen 32:30). The naming of the battlefield consecrates it as a site of YHWH's presence and power. The greater place-name theology is Golgotha — the place of the skull, renamed by what happened there as the place of the ultimate victory over death. The battlefield of the anointed one's apparent humiliation becomes the theological landmark of divine power.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samson judged Israel in the days of the Philistines twenty years. The judicial summary formula closes the first phase of Samson's career. Twenty years of judgment while Philistia remains dominant — he does not liberate Israel fully but keeps pressing against the oppressor. The prolonged partial reign of the deliverer who has not yet fully achieved his purpose is the pattern of the 'already/not yet' of Christ's kingdom: he has definitively defeated sin and death at the cross, yet the enemy is not yet finally destroyed (1 Cor 15:25-26: 'he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet'). The twenty years of Samson's partial judges typify the age of the Church, in which the deliverer has come and judged but the final victory is still pending.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>Samson goes to Gaza and sees a prostitute there and goes in to her. Gaza is the principal Philistine city — the deep enemy heartland. Samson's entry into Gaza repeats the pattern of ch14: the Spirit-empowered deliverer goes into the enemy's territory and is drawn by a woman there. The progression is downward: first a Philistine wife (ch14), then a prostitute in Gaza (ch16:1), then Delilah (ch16:4). Each transgression represents a deeper entanglement with the Philistine world. The Christological point of contrast: where Samson's passion for the wrong women draws him progressively deeper into enemy territory and eventual capture, Christ enters the enemy's territory (John 12:31: 'the ruler of this world') deliberately and sovereignly, not driven by passion but by the Father's love (John 3:16), and he exits by resurrection rather than betrayal.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Gazites surround Samson and wait all night at the city gate to kill him in the morning: 'When it is morning, we will kill him.' The ambush planned for morning is the enemy's strategy against the anointed one: wait for the appointed time, then strike. The same pattern governs the Passion: the chief priests plan to arrest Jesus quietly, wait for the right moment (Luke 22:2-6), and hand him over at dawn for crucifixion. But the morning that the enemies of YHWH's anointed plan for death becomes the morning of resurrection — the tomb is found empty at dawn on the first day (Mark 16:2; John 20:1). The Gazites' plan to kill at morning is undone by Samson's midnight escape; the Sanhedrin's plan for dawn execution is undone by the empty tomb.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Samson lies until midnight, then rises and takes the city gate posts — doors, two gateposts, bar and all — and puts them on his shoulders and carries them to the top of a hill near Hebron. The city gate was both the city's primary defense and its judicial center; to carry away the gate is to remove both the protection of the enemy city and the seat of its power. The typological significance is rich: Christ's harrowing of hell (1 Pet 3:18-20; Matt 16:18 — 'the gates of hell shall not prevail') and resurrection are figured as a carrying-away of death's gate. The city of the dead cannot hold the anointed one; he exits bearing the very mechanism of his containment on his shoulders. Isa 9:6 speaks of 'the government upon his shoulder' — here the government (the gate of the city) is carried on the deliverer's shoulders as a trophy of victory.</p>",
    "4": "<p>After this Samson loves a woman in the Valley of Sorek whose name is Delilah. The name Delilah possibly derives from <em>dallāh</em> (to weaken/make low) — a name encoding the narrative's theological function: she is the one through whom the strong is brought low. The Valley of Sorek is grape-country on the border of Philistia; its name (<em>śōrēq</em>, choice vine) evokes the vineyard imagery of Israel's covenant identity (Isa 5:1-7; Ps 80:8-9). The choice vine becomes the site of Samson's final vulnerability — love in the vineyard becoming the mechanism of betrayal, as the garden of Gethsemane becomes the site of Judas's betrayal of Jesus (Matt 26:36-47).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The five Philistine lords offer Delilah each 1100 pieces of silver to discover the source of Samson's strength. Five lords at 1100 pieces each totals 5500 pieces — the value placed on Samson's betrayal. The specificity of the price echoes the value placed on the betrayal of Christ (thirty pieces of silver, Matt 26:15) — both are the precise negotiated cost of handing over an anointed deliverer to his enemies. The use of a woman as the mechanism of betrayal for money is the amplified form of the ch14 pattern: the same dynamic of intimate betrayal for financial reward that prefigured Judas is here developed to its fullest expression before the final catastrophic betrayal of ch16.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Delilah asks Samson directly: 'Please tell me where your great strength lies, and how you might be bound, that one could subdue you.' The directness of the question — Delilah does not disguise her agenda — is part of the narrative's dark comedy: Samson lies to her three times yet keeps returning. The explicit request for the secret of his strength and the means of his binding is the enemy's abiding question about the source of the anointed one's power. The rulers who crucified Christ also misunderstood the source of his power and thought the cross would eliminate it; they did not know that his power flows from his relationship with the Father and that death would amplify rather than end it (John 10:17-18).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Samson gives his first false answer: seven fresh bowstrings not yet dried. The number seven in the context of Samson's Nazirite calling is significant: his seven locks (v19) are bound up with his consecration; here he proposes seven bowstrings as a false surrogate for the true source of his power. The number seven recurs across the three lies (seven bowstrings, new ropes, weaving of hair), marking each false answer as a parody of completeness. The enemy seeking the source of the anointed one's power consistently receives incomplete answers — 'none of the rulers of this age understood this, for if they had, they would not have crucified the Lord of glory' (1 Cor 2:8).</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Philistine lords bring Delilah the seven fresh bowstrings, and she binds Samson with them while men are lying in wait. The ambush men hidden in the inner room waiting for Delilah's signal establish the covert coordination between Delilah and the Philistine intelligence network — Samson's intimacy is being surveilled. The hidden watchers within the house of love are a type of the hidden forces that coordinated the Passion: 'Judas knew the place' (John 18:2), and the coordination was arranged in advance, with a prearranged signal (a kiss, Matt 26:48). The betrayal of the anointed one requires insider knowledge and coordinated action; it cannot happen by mere external force.</p>",
    "9": "<p>With the men waiting in ambush, Delilah cried to him, &lsquo;The Philistines are upon you, Samson!&rsquo; But he snapped the bowstrings as a strand of tow snaps when it touches fire. So the secret of his strength was not known. The first failed test establishes the narrative pattern that will repeat three times. Samson's effortless breaking of the bowstrings when the alarm is raised demonstrates that the source of his strength is not in any material object but in his relationship with YHWH. The same logic governs the NT's understanding of Christ's power: no external binding, no tomb, no seal can contain the power of the resurrection (Acts 2:24: 'God raised him up, loosing the pangs of death, because it was not possible for him to be held by it').</p>",
    "10": "<p>Delilah accuses Samson: 'You have mocked me and told me lies. Please tell me how you might be bound.' The accusation of mockery and lies — <em>hetel ʾōtî</em> (you have mocked/deceived me) — is legitimate from Delilah's perspective but covenantally invalid: Delilah is the enemy's agent, and Samson's deception of her is not a violation of covenant fidelity. The Christological parallel is the charge of deception brought against Christ: 'Sir, we remember how that impostor said' (Matt 27:63). The enemies who seek to bind the anointed one characterize his protection of the divine mystery as deception — because they cannot comprehend that truth has a right to protect itself from those who would weaponize it.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Samson offers his second lie: new ropes never used. The progression from bowstrings (weapon-equipment) to new ropes (general-purpose binding) escalates the apparent plausibility while maintaining the fiction. The new ropes recall Samson's voluntary submission to binding by the men of Judah in 15:13; there the ropes melted like flax before him when the Spirit came. The ropes that could not hold him in covenant solidarity with Israel certainly cannot hold him in Philistine captivity. The anointed one cannot be held by the bonds his enemies devise — only by the bonds he himself accepts.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Delilah binds Samson with new ropes while men lie in wait in the inner room; she cries 'The Philistines are upon you, Samson!' He breaks the ropes from his arms like a thread. The second failed test confirms the pattern: external bonds cannot contain Samson's Spirit-empowered strength. The tearing of ropes 'like a thread' echoes the great-strength tradition of Israel's heroes (Acts 16:26, where an earthquake breaks the stocks holding Paul and Silas). The liberation from bonds by divine power is the recurring sign of YHWH's championship of his anointed — from Joseph released from prison (Gen 41:14) to Peter released from chains (Acts 12:7) to Christ rising from the sealed tomb (Matt 28:2-6).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Samson gives his third lie: weave the seven locks of his hair into the web of a loom. This answer is closer to the truth than the previous two — the hair is mentioned, and the number seven reappears. The narrowing of the lies toward the truth is a narrative pressure that mirrors the escalating intimacy of the betrayal: each false answer is closer to the secret, each test more invasive. Delilah weaves his hair while he sleeps, and the peg is driven in — a foreshadowing of v19 where the actual shaving occurs during sleep. The sleeping vulnerable man in the lap of the woman who will betray him is the Passion picture in outline.</p>",
    "14": "<p>She pins it with the peg and cries 'The Philistines are upon you!' He wakes and goes away with the peg of the loom and the web — the third test fails. Samson waking with the loom's peg trailing from his hair is almost comic: the man who cannot be bound is leaving with his would-be binder attached. The absurdity of the successive failed attempts signals the narrative's theological point: the strength of the Spirit-anointed one is invulnerable to every external mechanism of control — bowstrings, ropes, even a woven bond attached to the very source of his strength. Only the voluntary disclosure of the secret can transfer the power; only Samson's own speech will deliver him.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Delilah presses: &lsquo;How can you say you love me when your heart is not with me? You have mocked me these three times.&rsquo; The accusation &lsquo;you do not love me&rsquo; is the emotional leverage that will finally break Samson&rsquo;s resistance (v16-17). The appeal to love as the ground of disclosure — &lsquo;if you loved me you would tell me&rsquo; — is the perversion of covenant intimacy: love is being weaponized to extract confession. The Gethsemane pattern reverses this: Christ does not need to extract confession from the Father because their love is perfect; he discloses himself fully not under emotional pressure but in the freedom of love (&lsquo;I lay down my life of my own accord,&rsquo; John 10:18).</p>",
    "16": "<p>When she pressed him hard with her words day after day, urging him, his soul was vexed to death (<em>wattāṣar napšô lāmût</em>). The phrase 'his soul was vexed to death' is the same Hebrew construction as the Gethsemane agony: 'My soul is very sorrowful, even to death' (<em>perilypos estin hē psychē mou heōs thanatou</em>, Matt 26:38). In both cases the anointed one's soul is pressed to the point of death by the one closest to him — Delilah's sustained pestering and the disciples' failure to watch with Jesus are both intimate failures that precede surrender to the enemy. Samson's soul pressed to death by Delilah's words; Christ's soul pressed to death in Gethsemane under the weight of human sin.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Delilah sends for the Philistine lords and they come with the money in their hands — the coins present at the moment of betrayal. 'She made him sleep on her knees, and called for a man and had him shave off the seven locks of his head.' The image of Samson asleep on Delilah's knees while the shaver removes his consecration is one of the OT's most charged moments of vulnerability: the deliverer stripped of his Nazirite sign in a state of trusting repose. The type of Christ is the sleeping in the garden: 'could you not watch with me one hour?' (Matt 26:40). In both cases the anointed one's rest in the place of apparent safety becomes the moment of his handing over.</p>",
    "19": "<p>She shaved off his seven locks; his strength left him (<em>wayyāsar kōḥô mēʿālāyw</em>). The departure of strength with the removal of the seven locks is the departure of the Spirit's empowerment — not because hair is intrinsically magical but because the Nazirite vow's integrity was the vessel of Samson's covenant relationship with YHWH, and its violation was the violation of that relationship. The seven locks shaved echoes the Nazirite legislation of Num 6:18 where the Nazirite's hair is shaved at the fulfillment of the vow — here it is shaved in betrayal rather than completion. The stripping of Samson's consecration is the typological precursor of Christ's stripping at the cross (Matt 27:28, 35) — the one who is fully consecrated to YHWH is stripped of every external mark of dignity by his enemies.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Philistines seize Samson, gouge out his eyes, bring him down to Gaza, bind him with bronze shackles, and he grinds grain in prison. Three acts of humiliation: blindness, binding, and servile labor. The blinding of the one who had seen the Timnite woman and Delilah — whose eyes had driven him to transgression — is the poetic justice of covenant discipline: the organ of his sin becomes the site of his punishment. The grinding of grain in prison is slave-woman's work (Exod 11:5; Isa 47:2). Christ's humiliation includes being bound (John 18:12), stripped, and mocked (Matt 27:27-31) — the anointed one reduced to the condition of a slave in fulfillment of Isa 53:3-5. The bronze shackles that bind Samson echo the bronze chains of Zedekiah (2 Kings 25:7) — two anointed leaders bound in bronze after covenant failure.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'But the hair of his head began to grow again after it had been shaved.' The single verse of hopeful reversal embedded in Samson's nadir is the narrative's resurrection announcement: the sign of consecration is returning. The growing of hair is biologically inevitable — it cannot be permanently removed. The type of resurrection is embedded in the structure of biology: cut off, it grows back; the Nazirite consecration cannot be permanently nullified. Christ's death has the same biological-theological structure: 'it was not possible for him to be held by it' (Acts 2:24). The hair growing in the dark of the prison is the resurrection seed germinating before any public announcement.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Philistine lords assemble to offer a great sacrifice to Dagon their god and to rejoice: 'Our god has given Samson our enemy into our hand.' The victory celebration over the captured deliverer is the pattern repeated at the cross: 'He saved others; he cannot save himself' (Matt 27:42); the mocking at Golgotha parallels the Philistine celebration — the apparent victory of the enemy over the anointed one. The specific attribution of Samson's capture to Dagon ('our god has given him into our hand') is the enemy's theological claim that their deity has defeated YHWH's judge. The premature victory celebration is invariably the sign of imminent overthrow: &lsquo;while people are saying there is peace and security, then sudden destruction will come upon them&rsquo; (1 Thess 5:3).</p>",
    "24": "<p>When the people see Samson, they praise their god: 'Our god has given our enemy into our hand, the ravager of our country who has killed many of us.' The corporate praise of Dagon for Samson's capture is the mirror image of Israel's victory songs — the same liturgical structure (see, praise, attribution to deity) deployed for the enemy's celebration. The theological reversal the narrative is building toward is that YHWH will receive the praise after Dagon's house falls: the praise currently given to Dagon will be silenced under the rubble of his own temple. The enemies of the anointed one who prematurely celebrate ('Let him come down from the cross and we will believe in him,' Matt 27:42) find their celebration turned to terror at the resurrection.</p>",
    "25": "<p>When their hearts are merry they call for Samson to be brought out to perform — <em>wᵉyᵉśaḥeq lānû</em>, 'that he may entertain us.' The word <em>śāḥaq</em> (laugh/sport/play) is the same root as Isaac's name — the one given as the instrument of YHWH's laughter at the enemies (Ps 2:4). Samson the judge is made to perform as a court jester before the Philistine lords. The humiliation of Christ before Herod's court — 'Herod with his soldiers treated him with contempt and mocked him' (Luke 23:11) — and before the Roman soldiers (Matt 27:27-31) is the NT fulfillment: the anointed one made to perform for his captors. Both Samson and Christ endure public mockery orchestrated by the enemy before the decisive act that ends the enemy's power.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Samson asks the young man who holds his hand to let him touch the pillars that support the house. Samson's blindness means he must be guided to the place of his final act — yet his request shows intentionality and planning: he knows what he will do when he reaches the pillars. The blind anointed one guided to the place of his final act is a type of Christ's Gethsemane prayer — knowing full well what is coming, walking deliberately toward it ('knowing all that would happen to him,' John 18:4). The anointed one is not carried to the site of his death; he goes to it with knowledge and purpose, submitting to being led only because the journey requires it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The house was full of men and women; all the Philistine lords were there, and about three thousand men and women on the roof watching. The assembly of Philistine power — lords, thousands, the entire leadership watching the sport — concentrates all the forces that have oppressed Israel into one structure above Samson's head. The 'about three thousand' on the roof recalls the three thousand who die at Sinai's golden calf (Exod 32:28) and the three thousand saved at Pentecost (Acts 2:41) — the same number marking covenant judgment and covenant inauguration. The crowd assembled to watch the anointed one's final performance is the same pattern as the crowd at the cross (Matt 27:39-44) — the public, mocking audience at the event that will transform history.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Samson grasps the two middle pillars on which the house rested — he leans his right hand on one and his left hand on the other. The posture of Samson with arms extended to both sides — right hand on one pillar, left hand on the other — is the cruciform posture of outstretched arms. The image of the anointed one with arms spread between two supports, with all the powers of the enemy arrayed above him, is one of the OT's most direct typological images of the cross. The two pillars flanking the central space may correspond to the two thieves flanking Christ at Golgotha (Matt 27:38). The structure Samson destroys is the house of Dagon — a false god whose worship will be ended by the very act of the anointed one's death.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Samson's brothers and his father's whole family come down, take his body, and bury him between Zorah and Eshtaol in the tomb of his father Manoah. The burial by family members in the ancestral tomb is the honorable burial accorded to a judge who fulfilled his calling. The Christological contrast: where Samson is buried in his father's tomb — the ancestral sepulcher of his family — Christ is buried in a borrowed tomb belonging to Joseph of Arimathea (Matt 27:60; Isa 53:9: 'they made his grave with the rich'). Both are accorded honorable burial by those who loved them; both burials are temporary. The note that Samson 'judged Israel twenty years' is the judge's formal legacy — Christ's legacy is 'all authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me' (Matt 28:18): not twenty years but forever.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, FILL)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'judges', c)

    import json as _j
    inter = _j.load(open(ROOT / 'data' / 'interlinear' / 'judges.json'))
    for ch in ['14', '15', '16']:
        total = len(inter[str(ch)])
        have = len(c.get(str(ch), {}))
        status = 'complete' if have == total else f'partial {have}/{total}'
        print(f'  ch {ch}: {status}')
    total_i = sum(len(v) for v in inter.values())
    total_h = sum(len(v) for v in c.values())
    print(f'  Overall judges/christ: {total_h}/{total_i}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
